gw.api.util

Class Range<T extends Object>

  • java.lang.Object
    • gw.api.util.Range<T>

  • public class Range<T extends Object>
extends Object
    Represents a value range, which can be open or closed at either end, or indefinite at either end. Examples:
    • All numbers between zero and one (exclusive) - [0, 1)
    • All strings between "S" and "T" (exclusive) - ["S", "T")
    • All positive numbers - (0, ∞)

    Intervals are typically over {@link Comparable} objects, but they can also be over non-{@link Comparable} objects, if a {@link java.util.Comparator} is supplied to the range.

    • Field Summary

      Fields 
      Modifier and Type Field and Description
      Comparator<Object> Comparator
      Gets the comparator used to define the range.
      boolean Empty
      Determines whether the given range is empty, i.e., whether {@link #includes(Object) includes(T)} will return false for every input.

      Note that it's possible to have ranges for which {@link #includes(Object) includes(T)} will always return false, but which return true for this method. This can happen when dealing with open ranges. For example, the integer range (0, 1) is not empty, but {@link #includes(Object) includes(T)} will always return false, because no integer exists between 0 and 1.
      Object End
      Gets the end of the range. Null if this range has no upper bound.
      boolean OpenEnd
      Whether the end of the range is open or closed, i.e., whether the end is included (closed) or not (open). Does not apply when end is null.
      boolean OpenStart
      Whether the start of the range is open or closed, i.e., whether the start is included (closed) or not (open). Does not apply when start is null.
      Object Start
      Gets the start of the range. Null if this range has no lower bound.
